{\plain \fs24 \f1 Radio address by Margaret Sanger on {\u8220\'93}My Experiences in India{\u8221\'94}\par
}\pard \fs24\qc\sl480\slmult1\tqr\tx9360 
{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Pittsburgh, Wednesday, 9 A.M.\par
}\pard \fs24\sl480\slmult1 
{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 Put in Header}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 \{Margaret Sanger is the President of the National \softline
Committee on Federal Legislation for Birth Control, and Director \softline
of the Birth Control Clinical Research bureau, America{\u8217\'92}s oldest \softline
and largest birth control clinic.  She went to India as \softline
representative of the Birth Control International Information \softline
Centre, London, of which she is also the President.\}\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \ul0 \tab In India, where I spent a good part of the past year, there \softline
is a proverb: {\u8220\'93}Wisdom is knowing what to do, skill is knowing how \softline
to do it but virtue is in the doing it.{\u8221\'94}  As I go from country to \softline
country, from city to city, through the world, I am convinced \softline
that in America today we have the wisdom, the knowledge and the \softline
skill, in knowing what to do and how to solve our problems, but \softline
we do not have }{\plain \fs24 \strike\f1 the virtue}{\plain \fs24 \f1  {\f2 \'38}that thing call it virtue, courage or \softline
[initiative?]{\f2 \'39} to do it.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab I was invited to come to India by the All India Woman{\u8217\'92}s \softline
Conference, representing between eleven and twelve millions of \softline
the most intelligent women of the Orient.  I was greatly \softline
surprised that so many women in India spoke English and were well \softline
informed about problems which we in the West are so futilely \softline
trying to solve.  I was also surprised to find that not only 
educated Indians, particularly doctors and social workers, were \softline
willing and eager to find some way of dealing with \softline
overpopulation, but that men and women of all classes were \softline
pathetically anxious to learn about birth control.  Women begged \softline
and pleaded for information about how to limit their families and \softline
space their children.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 \ul0 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \f1 This was not at all what I had been led to expect in India.   \softline
People who claimed to be familiar with conditions, with whom I \softline
had talked before I landed in Bombay, were pessimistic.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab {\u8220\'93}Their religion makes it an Indian woman{\u8217\'92}s highest duty to \softline
have children,{\u8221\'94} I was told.  {\u8220\'93}The more she has the better she \softline
likes it.{\u8221\'94}\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab One highly educated Indian man said to me: {\u8220\'93}Why, Mrs. \softline
Sanger, you can do nothing.  We all admit that birth control is \softline
the only answer to India{\u8217\'92}s population problem, but the women \softline
themselves don{\u8217\'92}t want it.{\u8221\'94}\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab I was sure they were wrong.  I have always been sure that \softline
women in all lands and all ages have instinctively desired family \softline
spacing.  I was sure that in a land like India, where you find \softline
women seeking a new freedom, economic and social, there would be \softline
thousands of minds reaching out to find knowledge which would \softline
mean freedom.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab So I said nothing, {\f2 \'38}but waited.{\f2 \'39}  I wanted to learn for \softline
myself whether the women of India were so different from the 
women fo any other country in the world, that they wanted and \softline
would cling to endless childbearing if the way to voluntary \softline
motherhood were opened to them.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Just two days after I arrived in Bombay I went to the \softline
{\u8220\'93}chawls,{\u8221\'94} the long rows of tenement houses where the city{\u8217\'92}s mill \softline
workers are crowded together in small dark rooms.  Children, \softline
their naked little bodies bone-thin, played in the streets, or \softline
sat listlessly in the shadow of the buildings.  Mothers stared \softline
with inert eyes.  Almost every one had a baby or small child on \softline
her hip.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab I knew that of every 1000 children born in Bombay, 298 die.  \softline
I know that it has been estimated that 100 of every 1000 mothers \softline
in India die in childbirth.  I looked at these poor, worn out \softline
women, at their undernourished, undersized children.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab {\u8220\'93}Ask this mother how many children she has,{\u8221\'94} I said to the \softline
social worker who accompanied me, {\f2 \'38}and{\f2 \'39} pointed to a woman in a \softline
ragged sari, squatting on the street, holding a baby in her arms.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab {\u8220\'93}Six,{\u8221\'94} was the answer.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab {\u8220\'93}And how many dead?{\u8221\'94}, I asked.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab {\u8220\'93}Five{\u8221\'94}, she answered.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab {\u8220\'93}And how many more do you want,{\u8221\'94} I pursued.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab She threw out her hands in a pathetic gesture.  A look of \softline
fear came into her tired, lined face.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab {\u8220\'93}Please God, no more!{\u8221\'94}\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \ul0 \tab We talked to scores of mothers, some old, some young, and \softline
they all echoed the words, {\u8220\'93}Please God, no more.{\u8221\'94}\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab No Bombay man can again tell me that women of this city, or \softline
any city in India do not want information which will free them of \softline
the dread of bringing children into the world to rob those they \softline
already have of food and clothing and care, of the very breath of \softline
life.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Every moment }{\plain \fs24 \strike\f1 from my arrival}{\plain \fs24 \f1  {\f2 \'38}of my stay{\f2 \'39} in India was \softline
crowded with meetings and conferences, with interviews and \softline
lectures.  The problem was not how to meet opposition, for there \softline
are no legal restrictions, such as we have in America, and \softline
practically no religious opposition.  The task was how to train \softline
doctors, midwives and nurses, to organize clinics, and put the \softline
movement on a firm, scientific foundation as a public health \softline
measure.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Birth control is a burning question in India, and those best \softline
qualified to understand India{\u8217\'92}s problems are aware of this.  \softline
According to Major General Megaw, medical adviser to the \softline
Secretary of State for India, the population is rapidly \softline
outstripping industrial production and the situation can best be \softline
summed up in words {\u8220\'93}They do not get enough to eat.{\u8221\'94}  Experts \softline
agree that by 1941, when the next census is taken, India{\u8217\'92}s \softline
population may well number four hundred millions.\par
